{
  "id": "phase-rs_phase_1690",
  "repo_name": "phase-rs/phase",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/phase-rs/phase",
  "base_commit": "3991e993f6f9757ffdc6842420352f71a2dce7ed",
  "pr_number": 1690,
  "issue_number": 1689,
  "issue_title": "[Bug]: APNAP trigger ordering uses a binary active/non-active key instead of full turn order, breaking CR 603.3b/CR 101.4 in 3+ player games",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\nIn `crates/engine/src/game/triggers.rs`, when multiple abilities trigger simultaneously the engine orders them with a **binary** \"is this the active player?\" key. Every *non-active* player is collapsed into a single bucket ordered only by timestamp, so in games with two or more non-active players (Commander / multiplayer) the triggers are not put on the stack in turn order as the Comprehensive Rules require.\n\n```rust\n// crates/engine/src/game/triggers.rs:1825\n// CR 603.3b: Active player's triggers are ordered before non-active player's triggers.\n// Within same controller, order by timestamp.\npending.sort_by_key(|t| {\n    let is_nap = if t.pending.controller == state.active_player {\n        0\n    } else {\n        1\n    };\n    (is_nap, t.pending.timestamp)   // <- all non-active players share rank 1\n});\n\n// Reverse so NAP triggers are placed first (bottom of stack), AP triggers last (top).\npending.reverse();\n```\n\nThe `is_nap` key is `0` for the active player and `1` for **every** non-active player, with `timestamp` as the only tiebreaker. That cannot reproduce turn order among multiple non-active players.\n\n## What the CR requires\n\nVerified verbatim against `docs/MagicCompRules.txt`:\n\n```\n603.3b If multiple abilities have triggered since the last time a player received priority,\n       each player, in APNAP order, puts triggered abilities they control on the stack\n       in an order of their choosing. (See rule 101.4.) ...\n101.4  If multiple players would make choices ... the active player ... makes any choices\n       required, then the next player in turn order ... followed by the remaining nonactive\n       players in turn order. ...\n```\n\nSo abilities are placed on the stack in **APNAP order**: the active player first, then **each remaining player in turn order** \u2014 not \"active player, then all non-active players lumped together by timestamp.\"\n\nThe codebase already has the correct helper, `players::apnap_order` (`crates/engine/src/game/players.rs:78`):\n\n```rust\n/// CR 101.4: APNAP (Active Player, Non-Active Player) ordering.\n/// Returns living players in APNAP order, starting from the active player\n/// and proceeding in seat order.\npub fn apnap_order(state: &GameState) -> Vec<PlayerId> { ... }\n```\n\nIt is used for player-choice sequencing in ~10 other modules (`casting.rs`, `combat.rs`, `effects/vote.rs`, `effects/explore.rs`, `effects/choose_and_sacrifice_rest.rs`, `effects/separate_piles.rs`, `engine.rs`, \u2026) \u2014 but the trigger sort sites in `triggers.rs` do not use it.\n\n## Failure mode (concrete example)\n\n4-player Commander game (a supported, tested format \u2014 `GameState::new(FormatConfig::commander(), 4, \u2026)`), seat order `[P0, P1, P2, P3]`, and it is **P1's turn** (`state.active_player = P1`).\n\nA single simultaneous event (e.g. a board-wide `PhaseChanged`, or one creature's ETB seen by several permanents) triggers one ability controlled by **P2** and one controlled by **P0**, where P0's trigger source entered the battlefield earlier (smaller `timestamp`) than P2's.\n\n- **Correct APNAP turn order from active P1:** P1, **P2, P3, P0**. P2 is the first non-active player, so P2 chooses the order of / places its trigger before P0, and (under LIFO) P0's trigger resolves before P2's.\n- **Current engine:** P0 and P2 both get `is_nap = 1`; P0's smaller timestamp sorts it first, so **P0 is placed and prompted before P2** \u2014 inverting both the stack-resolution order and the interactive trigger-ordering prompt order.\n\nThis changes observable game state: which trigger resolves first, and which player is asked to order their triggers first.\n\n## Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Start a 3- or 4-player game where the active player is not seat 0 (e.g. active = P1, seats `[P0,P1,P2,P3]`).\n2. Cause a single event to trigger one ability controlled by P0 and one controlled by P2, with P0's source older (smaller timestamp).\n3. Observe trigger placement/resolution order: P0's resolves after P2's (engine) instead of P0 before P2 (rules), and P0 is prompted to order before P2.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nSimultaneously-triggered abilities are placed on the stack in full APNAP turn order (active player, then each remaining player in turn order per CR 101.4), with each controller free to order its own triggers among themselves.\n\n## Actual behavior\n\nTriggers are ordered by a binary active/non-active key plus a timestamp tiebreaker, so all non-active players are treated as one group ordered by timestamp rather than by turn order.\n\n## Affected code paths\n\nThe same binary-key defect is duplicated at three sort sites:\n\n- `triggers.rs:1825` \u2014 pending (just-triggered) abilities, tiebreaker `t.pending.timestamp`.\n- `triggers.rs:3069` \u2014 state-triggered abilities, tiebreaker `t.timestamp`.\n- `triggers.rs:3128` \u2014 delayed-triggered abilities, tiebreaker `state.turn_number` (even coarser).\n\n## Suggested fix\n\n- Replace the binary `is_nap` rank with each controller's index in `players::apnap_order(state)` (0 = active player, then non-active players in turn order), keeping the existing timestamp tiebreaker for intra-controller order and the existing `reverse()` for stack placement. In a 2-player game the index is `0`/`1`, identical to today's behavior, so nothing regresses.\n- Apply the same change at all three sort sites.\n- Add fail-on-revert coverage in a 3-/4-player game with the active player not in seat 0 and two non-active players whose timestamps disagree with turn order. The existing `order_triggers_apnap_three_players` test exercises only a single non-active player, so the binary key passes by coincidence and the bug is untested.",
